commit.message: attempt to document better distributive functors
IndexZ/IndexS were renamed to IZ and IS, added KnownIZ and KnownIS
fix typos and delete obsolete comment
remove `Representable f` constraint from Monoid instance for Logarithm

use alternative definition of tabulateLogarithm

This one is easier to understand, though less mechanical

Remove unneeded CPP

This CPP is no longer needed due to `distributive` only supporting
GHC 8.6 or later.

Fix a -Wnoncanonical-monad-instances warning

This shows up with -Wall on GHC 9.2, which adds
-Wnoncanonical-monad-instances to -Wall.

Fix a -Woperator-whitespace-ext-conflict warning

This shows up with -Wall on GHC 9.2, which adds
-Woperator-whitespace-ext-conflict to -Wall.

Relax some uses of DerivingVia to DerivingStrategies

I was too overzealous in my earlier commit, as it turns out that we don't need
the full power of `DerivingVia` in some place, just `DerivingStrategies`. This
allows us to restore some uses of `Safe` (rather than using `Trustworthy`).

Use Trustworthy, rather than Safe, in combination with DerivingVia

As of GHC 9.0.2, `DerivingVia` is disallowed with `Safe` (see
https://gitlab.haskell.org/ghc/ghc/-/merge_requests/5675). This changes the
affected uses of `Safe` to `Trustworthy` where needed.

commit.message:
Adapt to proxy# having different specificities across GHC versions

Prior to GHC 8.10, the kind variable in the type of `proxy#` was specified,
whereas in 8.10 or later, it it inferred. See
https://gitlab.haskell.org/ghc/ghc/-/issues/16293. As a result,
`proxy# @(a :: k)` is well kinded on 8.10 or later, but not on older GHCs.
Bummer.

This works around the issue by using `proxy# :: Proxy# (a :: k)` instead, which
should be compatible with all supported GHC versions.
